🧠 Part 1 — “Wikipedia paths” as a learning signal

What the game gives you

Each playthrough is a path on a graph:

* nodes = pages (concepts)
* edges = links (relationships)
* path = a sequence of choices

From many paths you can extract:

* common routes (high-frequency patterns)
* shortcuts (efficient reasoning)
* detours (where people get confused)
* biases (popular but suboptimal jumps)

Turn it into data (without overreach)

Instead of “pseudorandom,” think:

diverse, human-shaped path data with controllable noise

You can augment safely by:

* randomizing start/end pairs
* shuffling equivalent nodes (synonyms/categories)
* adding small perturbations (skip/insert a step)

What you learn (useful features)

* Path length vs. optimal length (efficiency)
* Node centrality (which concepts act as hubs)
* Edge reliability (which links consistently help)
* Cross-domain jumps (where metaphors/bridges happen)

What it’s good for

* Traversal policies (how to move through a knowledge graph)
* Compression (learn minimal routes → “constellations that hold up”)
* Retrieval (find good bridges between distant ideas)

Guardrails

* Don’t treat paths as ground truth—they’re heuristics.
* Validate with your earlier rule:
    keep what stays consistent across different runs/cues; drop the rest

